<DOC><DOCNO> AP880406-0265 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-88 1541EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-DividendReport     04-06 0185</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Dividend Report,0192</SECOND><HEAD>Report Finds Quarterly Corporate Dividends Up Slightly</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Slightly more companies raised theirfirst-quarter dividends over a year ago, reflecting an increasedconfidence that the economy isn't headed into a recession followingthe stock market crash, Standard andamp; Poor's Corp. reported Tuesday.   For the first three months of 1988, dividend increases rose 4.8percent, to 482 from 460 in 1987, Sandamp;P said. At the same time,decreased and omitted dividends fell to 47 from 58 in the quarter,it said.   ``The rebound in dividend increases shows that fears of arecession due to the market crash have abated,'' said ArnieKaufman, editor of Sandamp;P's Outlook newsletter.   ``Recovery in the manufacturing sector is enabling many formerlydepressed businesses to participate in dividend largesse afteryears of struggling to merely hold the line.''   Despite the Oct. 19 stock collapse, Kaufman said corporationswere optimistic the economy would continue to expand this yearbecause of recent upbeat trade, employment and consumer spendingreports.   Companies reporting dividend actions to Sandamp;P comprise asubstantial portion of all public companies in the United States.</TEXT></DOC>